 the books, or carried the bricks that made Germany a great nation. This book contains translated selections from the autobiographies of nineteen of those now-forgotten millions. The thirteen men and six women who speak from these pages afford an intimate firsthand look at how massive social and economic changes are reflected on a personal level in the everyday lives of workers. Although some of these autobiographies are familiar to specialists in German labor history, they are virtually unknown and inaccessible to the broader audience they deserve. This book provides translations that are at once useful, interesting, and entertaining to a wide range of historians, students, and general readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aProletariatxHistory. 0aWorking classzGermanyvBiography. 0aWorking classzGermanyxBiography. 0aWorking classzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  abarmaid.  abrickyard.  acapitalism.  achild labor.  achild worker.  acigar maker.  aclay miner.  acoal miner.  acoal mines.  acook.  aeconomics.  afactory worker.  afarm worker.  afarming.  agermany.  aglass grinder.  ahistory.  ahousehold labor.  ahousehold staff.  aindustrialization.  alabor conditions.  alabor relations.  alabor.  amachine age.  amaid.  amarxism.  ametalworker.  amigrant workers.  amines.  anonfiction.  arailroad.  aseamstress.  aservant.  asocial change.  atextiles.  awaiter.  aweaver.  awomen and labor.  awomen in factories.  awoodworker.  aworkers rights.  aworkers.  aworkhouse.  aworking class.1 aKelly, Alfred, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps